        "egyptian-inventions": {
            "id": "egyptian-inventions",
            "summary": "They discover Egyptian innovations still used today",
            "text": "Meru shows them various innovations. 'We Egyptians have contributed much to human knowledge.'\n\n'The calendar‚Äîour year has 365 days, divided into twelve months. We were the first to create this system. Before us, people tracked time only by the moon, which caused chaos for planning.'\n\n'Medicine‚Äîour doctors diagnose diseases, perform surgery, set broken bones. We know which plants heal fevers, infections, pain. Much of our knowledge we write down so future doctors can learn.'\n\n'Mathematics‚Äînot just for pyramids. We calculate land areas for farming, predict the Nile's flood levels, track grain storage. Our number system makes complex calculations possible.'\n\n{{PLAYER2_NAME}} is amazed. 'All this thousands of years ago?'\n\n'Paper too,' Meru adds, holding up papyrus. 'Made from reeds. Lightweight, portable, able to hold ink. Before papyrus, writing meant carving stone or pressing clay. How limiting!'\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} looks at the scarab in {{PLAYER1_HIS_HER}} hand. 'So much of what we use today started here.'",
